tion":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Rivington (Lancs). Medieval forms of this name are often indistinguishable from those for Rowington (Warwicks), but note Robertus Rivingtonman, 1379 in   Poll Tax   (Weeton, WR Yorks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Poll Tax","meanings":["1  Irish, Scottish Gaelic: relationship name: apparently a reduced form of an unrecorded Gaelic name,  <b>Mac Ruanaidh</b> ‘son of  <i>Ruanadh</i>’, a personal name from Gaelic  <i>ruanaidh</i> ‘strong man, champion’. The initial  <i>C</i> comes from the final consonant of  <i>mac</i>.  Compare  Rooney  .","2  English: of uncertain origin. It might be a variant of   Crowner   ‘coroner’, once a Sussex name, with the final syllable pronounced  <i>-ey</i>. Compare Simon Croner, 1296 in   Subsidy Rolls   (Horton, Tottington, and Edburton, Sussex); Willelmus Croner, 1379 in   Poll Tax   (South Mundham, Sussex). Alternatively it might be a variant of  <i>Corney</i> with the medial  <i>-r-</i> metathesized."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Rivington was born in 1335, in Brads